ğŸ’¡ Parameter Fuzzing TL;DR
Type	URL Placement	ffuf Flag	When to Use	Note
GET	In the query string (?FUZZ=value)	-u	To discover hidden GET params	Easiest to spot
POST	In the body (param=FUZZ)	-X POST -d	When backend uses POST forms	Add content-type
Value	Replace the value (param=FUZZ)	-d or -u	To find correct ID/Token/Key	Can brute force
ğŸ§  "Got This? Do That" Fuzzing Flow
ğŸ” 1. Discovered a Page That Says "Access Denied" or Looks Role-Sensitive?
â†’ Try GET parameter fuzzing

bash
Copy
Edit
ffuf -w burp-parameter-names.txt:FUZZ \
     -u http://target/page.php?FUZZ=value \
     -fs [default_response_size]
âœ” Filters out false positives
âœ” Use -mc if 403s matter
âœ” Visit any 200s manually

ğŸ› ï¸ 2. You Think the Backend Uses Forms or POST Auth?
â†’ Try POST parameter fuzzing

bash
Copy
Edit
ffuf -w burp-parameter-names.txt:FUZZ \
     -u http://target/page.php \
     -X POST -d 'FUZZ=value' \
     -H 'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' \
     -fs [default_response_size]
âœ” If you get new response size/status â†’ potential hidden logic
âœ” If unsure, replay with curl or Burp

ğŸ” 3. Found a Parameter, but Now You Need the Right Value?
â†’ Fuzz Parameter Values

âœ… Build a list of likely values:

bash
Copy
Edit
seq 1 1000 > ids.txt
ğŸ”¥ Fuzz it:

bash
Copy
Edit
ffuf -w ids.txt:FUZZ \
     -u http://target/page.php \
     -X POST -d 'id=FUZZ' \
     -H 'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' \
     -fs [default_response_size]
âœ” Could be:

Numeric IDs

UUIDs

API keys

Role values (admin, staff, etc)

You could also try things like: -w usernames.txt:FUZZ -d 'user=FUZZ' if testing access by username

ğŸ’£ Pro Tips
Always check page source code, JS files, or Burp history for parameter clues

Donâ€™t just test with â€œkeyâ€ â€” try known values, case flips, even empty (=, =0)

FFUF Filters:

-fs = filter by response size (used most)

-fc = filter by response code

-fw = filter by word count (optional but dope when responses are similar)

